result.execSummary:
The defendant Brittany N Prestwood was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manuf/Deliver Amphetamine(>3-10g), a class E felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(e)2.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Completed ERP 10/28/19 signed SLH
of SEH on 10/6/15 - Michelle S
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief filed

3:37 PM - Def in court w/ Atty Jennifer S Kovari.  Def in custody.  Justine L. Suleski appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
KOVARI: the Atty's weren't aware of the pregnancy at the time of the sentencing. I would have framed my argument differently SULESKI: objecting to mod of the sentence. The def knew at the time of sentencing and wanted to keep it private and now wants it to be out to avoid prison and I don't know if that's a new factor. I don't know if we want to risk the health of her child by letting her prove that this time she can be better. The def  knew this at the time of sentencing and now she wants to tell you about it so she can have a different outcome. CRT: def counsel has correctly stated the def of new facts. I accept Kovari's rep that it would have affected the sent argument she made. However the standard isn't whether a factor which was then in existence.  The def knew she was aware of the preg and there were family considerations that caused her to conceal this from her family and concealed - it was a strategic and wilfull decision on her part to conceal it from her counsel and the court. Secondly, I can't say that it would have been  highly relevant to the sentence. She would not be the first inmate to give birth in custody. The DOC has the responsibility of providing care to inmates and I assume w/ her and her preg that they would fulfill that obligation. As the ADA stated, it's an argument that can really cut both ways - that she should be given consideration for the child but the counter argument is that weighs in favor of prison as that would be the most effective way to protect the child but I don't know if I would have considered either of those to be highly relevant at sentencing.  I will find there is not a new factor and DENY  the mtn for reconsideration
to Modify Sentence
signed TWB
